SIMPLE: mump
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mump
<hw>Mump</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Akin to
<ets>mumble</ets>; cf. D. <ets>mompen</ets> to cheat; perh. orig., to
whine like a beggar, D. <ets>mompelen</ets> to mumble. See
<er>Mumble</er>, <er>Mum</er>, and cf. <er>Mumps</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To move the lips with the mouth closed; to mumble, as
in sulkiness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>mumps</qex>, and lovers, and hangs the lip.</q>
<rj><qau>Taylor, 1630.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To talk imperfectly, brokenly, or feebly; to chatter
unintelligibly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cheat; to deceive; to play the beggar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And then when <qex>mumping</qex> with a sore leg, . . . canting
and whining.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be sullen or sulky.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mump
<hw>Mump</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mumped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mumping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter imperfectly,
brokenly, or feebly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Old men who <qex>mump</qex> their passion.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To work over with the mouth; to mumble; <as>as, to
<ex>mump</ex> food</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deprive of (something) by cheating; to impose
upon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mumper</ent>⟦br⟧
